FILL_CH8 = {
  "8": {
    "1": "<p><strong>syneudokōn</strong> (<em>syneudokōn</em>, 'consenting/approving'): Paul will later describe his own role at Stephen's death with the same verb (22:20) — he was not a passive bystander but an active approver. <strong>diōgmos megas</strong> (<em>diōgmos megas</em>, 'great persecution'): the first use of <em>diōgmos</em> in Acts; the persecution Paul later says he suffered becomes the persecution he first caused (Gal 1:13; 1 Cor 15:9).</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>andres eulabeis</strong> (<em>andres eulabeis</em>, 'devout men'): the same adjective used for Simeon (Luke 2:25) and Cornelius (Acts 10:2). These are Torah-observant Jews honoring a fellow-Jew whom they recognized as righteous; their mourning (<em>penthountes</em>) was public and costly — lamentation for one executed as a criminal was itself a social risk.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>elymaineto</strong> (<em>elymaineto</em>, 'was ravaging/destroying'): a verb used in LXX for wild animals tearing flesh (Ps 80:13); its application to Saul's house-to-house arrests is deliberately brutal. <strong>syron</strong> (<em>syrōn</em>, 'dragging'): the violent participle conveys forced arrest — men and women dragged from their homes and thrown into prison. This is Paul's own retrospective self-condemnation (1 Tim 1:13: 'the chief of sinners').</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>hoi men oun diasparentes</strong> (<em>hoi men oun diasparentes</em>, 'those who were scattered'): <em>diaspeirō</em> (scatter, disperse) is the diaspora verb; the persecution that intended to suppress the gospel instead geographically expands it. Luke's narrative irony is deliberate: the enemy's strategy becomes the mission's vehicle. <strong>euangelizomenoi</strong> (proclaiming good news): the scattered are not refugees in silence but active evangelists.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>Philippos ... ekērysso autois ton Christon</strong> (<em>Philippos ... ekērysso autois ton Christon</em>, 'Philip proclaimed the Messiah to them'): Philip is the deacon (6:5) whose mission reaches Samaria — the next step in Acts 1:8's geographic outline. <em>Kēryssō</em> (herald-proclamation) is the strong word for authoritative announcement; its object is the Messiah-title, the full Jewish category that requires hermeneutical explanation.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>homothymadon</strong> (with one accord): the same word as Pentecost (2:1, 46), now describing the Samaritan crowd's unified attention. <strong>sēmeia ha epoiei</strong> (signs he was doing): the signs are the confirmation that the proclamation is authentic — same pattern as Peter and Paul. The Samaritans, traditionally estranged from Jerusalem, respond with the same unity as the Jerusalem crowd.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>pneumata akatharta ... exērchetho</strong> (impure spirits were coming out): <em>akatharta</em> (unclean) is the ritual-purity vocabulary applied to the demonic realm — the mission in Samaria addresses both spiritual and physical disorder. <strong>parelymenoi kai chōloi etherapeuonto</strong> (paralyzed and lame were healed): the two categories appear in the Isa 35:6 messianic-sign list, echoing Peter's temple healing.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>egeneto chara megalē</strong> (<em>egeneto chara megalē</em>, 'there was great joy'): joy is Luke's theological signal for eschatological arrival (Luke 2:10; 24:52; Acts 2:46; 13:52; 15:3; 16:34). The Samaritan city's joy marks the mission's reach into the traditionally excluded Samaritans; the kingdom's arrival is experienced as joy wherever it goes.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>mageuōn</strong> (<em>mageuōn</em>, 'practicing sorcery/magic'): the root gives us 'magic'; Simon is not merely a conjurer but someone operating within the framework of Hellenistic magical practice — invoking divine names and powers for results. <strong>existanōn</strong> (amazing): the same verb Philip's signs produce (v.6); Simon's amazement-capacity is about to be displaced by a greater power.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>hē dynamis tou theou hē kaloumenē Megalē</strong> (<em>hē dynamis tou theou hē kaloumenē Megalē</em>, 'the power of God called Great'): Simon's title is a Samaritan divine-name, likely connected to Simonian Gnosticism's later 'Great Power' theology. Luke preserves the exact wording — a measure of accuracy about a religious milieu his audience would recognize. Philip's proclamation of Jesus as Lord displaces Simon's self-claimed divine-power identity.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>dia to hikanō chronō tais mageiais existakenai autous</strong> ('because for a long time he had amazed them with his sorceries'): <em>hikanos chronos</em> (a long/considerable time) measures the depth of Simon's hold on the community; the Samaritans are not casually credulous but have been formed by years of his practice. Philip's sudden displacement of Simon signals the superior power of the gospel's witness.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>euangelizomenō peri tēs basileias tou theou kai tou onomatos Iēsou Christou</strong> ('proclaiming the good news about the kingdom of God and the name of Jesus Christ'): the two objects — kingdom and name — are the content of the Samaritan proclamation. Both men and women (<em>andres te kai gynaikes</em>) are baptized; the mission to Samaria includes women from the beginning, consistent with Acts' consistent inclusion of women in the covenant community.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>ho de Simōn kai autos episteusen</strong> ('Simon himself also believed'): Luke records Simon's belief and baptism factually; the subsequent exchange (vv.18-24) does not retract the belief but reveals its inadequate root. <strong>theōrōn ... dynameis kai sēmeia ginomena</strong> ('seeing the signs and great miracles happening'): Simon's continued astonishment is not penitential but acquisitive — he watches as a professional assessor of power.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>aposteilan pros autous Petron kai Iōannēn</strong> (sent Peter and John): Jerusalem's apostolic response to Samaritan conversion establishes continuity with the mother-community; the Samaritans are not a breakaway sect but an extension of the one church. The Jerusalem apostles' visit is the structural incorporation of Samaria into the body that began at Pentecost.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>hopōs labōsin pneuma hagion</strong> (so that they might receive the Holy Spirit): the separation between belief/baptism and Spirit-reception here is the strongest in Acts; it has generated debate about whether this was a temporary transitional phenomenon (incorporating Samaria required apostolic laying on of hands) or a normative two-stage pattern. The delay is not explained; Luke presents the apostolic prayer and hands as the channel for the Spirit's arrival.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>oupō gar ēn ep' oudeni autōn epipeptōkos</strong> ('for he had not yet fallen on any of them'): <em>epipiptō</em> (fall upon) is the Pentecost-verb (10:44; 11:15); its conspicuous absence here makes the contrast pointed. The Spirit who fell on 120 in Jerusalem without laying on of hands had not fallen on the Samaritan believers who had received baptism — the anomaly drives the narrative forward.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>epetithoun tas cheiras</strong> (they were laying their hands on them): the apostolic laying on of hands as the instrument for Spirit-reception appears here for the first time in Acts. The gesture has OT precedent (Num 8:10; 27:18-23) for commissioning and authorization; its use here extends that tradition to Spirit-reception, making the apostles' bodily action the channel of the divine gift.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>theōn hoti dia tēs epithesesōs tōn cheirōn tōn apostolōn didotai to Pneuma</strong> ('seeing that through the laying on of the apostles' hands the Spirit was given'): Simon sees something visible — the Spirit's reception was evidentially manifest, likely through speaking in tongues. His response reveals that he has processed Philip's entire ministry as a power-system with a controlling mechanism he could learn to operate.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>dos kai emoi tēn exousian tautēn</strong> ('give me also this authority'): <em>exousia</em> (authority, right) is precisely what Simon thinks he wants — the ability to transmit the Spirit by personal action. He misidentifies the Spirit's gift as a power that belongs to the apostles and can be purchased from them. The sin of simony names a category of ecclesiastical corruption after this episode.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>to argyrion sou syn soi eiē eis apōleian</strong> ('may your money go to destruction with you'): Peter's response is the sharpest rebuke in Acts — not a question but a wish-formula invoking divine judgment. <strong>hoti tēn dōrean tou theou enomisas dia chrēmatōn ktasthai</strong> ('because you thought you could acquire the gift of God with money'): <em>dōrea</em> (gift, v.20) echoes 2:38; the Spirit is given, never purchased.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>ouk estin soi meris oud' klēros en tō logō toutō</strong> ('you have no part or share in this word'): <em>meris</em> and <em>klēros</em> are the inheritance-vocabulary of covenant participation — the same terms used for Judas's forfeited portion (1:17, 25). Simon's heart (<em>hē kardia sou ouk estin eutheia enanti tou theou</em>) is the diagnostic: not the money but the disposition of heart is what disqualifies.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>metanōeson apo tēs kakias tautes</strong> ('repent of this wickedness'): Peter's imperative is conditional but genuine — repentance is possible and offered. <strong>ei ara aphethēsetai soi hē epinoia tēs kardias sou</strong> ('if perhaps the thought of your heart may be forgiven'): the <em>ei ara</em> (if perhaps) is an unusual conditional that indicates uncertainty about whether the intent is forgivable — not denying God's forgiveness but questioning Simon's sincerity.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>cholēn pikrias kai syndesmō adikias</strong> ('gall of bitterness and bond of wickedness'): <em>cholē pikria</em> (gall of bitterness) echoes Deut 29:18 LXX for the root of apostasy — a root of poison-plant. <em>Syndesmos adikias</em> (bond of unrighteousness) describes being bound up in sin's system. Peter's diagnosis reaches back to OT prophetic categories for describing the state of someone whose orientation is fundamentally against the covenant.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>deēthēte hymeis hyper emou pros ton kyrion</strong> ('pray to the Lord for me'): Simon's request — asking others to pray for him rather than praying himself — may indicate genuine fear without genuine repentance. The ambiguity is deliberate; Luke does not close the question of Simon's ultimate state. The narrative serves as a warning rather than a resolution.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>hypestraphon eis Ierousalēm ... euēngelizonto pollas kōmas tōn Samaritōn</strong> ('they returned to Jerusalem, proclaiming good news to many Samaritan villages'): the apostles' return journey through Samaritan villages is a quiet expansion of the mission. The same apostles sent from Jerusalem to evaluate the Samaritan mission become missionaries in Samaritan villages on their way home — the mission spreads through every movement.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>angelos de kyriou elalēsen pros Philippon</strong> (an angel of the Lord spoke to Philip): divine direction by angel (also 5:19; 10:3; 12:7-11; 27:23) is Luke's way of marking pivotal mission-transitions. The road to Gaza is described as <em>autē estin erēmos</em> ('this is a desert [road]') — either the road is remote or Gaza itself was ruined after its destruction in 96 BC. Philip is redirected from successful urban mission to an isolated road encounter.</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>dynastēs Kandakēs basylissēs Aithiopōn</strong> ('an official of Candace, queen of the Ethiopians'): <em>dynastēs</em> (high official, powerful person) is a court title; Candace was the title of the queen mother in Meroitic Nubia, who effectively ruled. Ethiopia (<em>Aithiopia</em>) represented the southern end of the known world; this official is both the 'ends of the earth' (Acts 1:8) and a diaspora worshipper connecting the mission to its furthest geographic range.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>anaginōskōn ton prophētēn Esaian</strong> (reading the prophet Isaiah): ancient reading was typically oral — <em>anaginōskōn</em> implies reading aloud, which is why Philip could hear what the eunuch was reading from a distance. The Isaiah scroll was among the most expensive texts in the first century; this official was both literate and wealthy enough to own the text. Luke's detail explains the mechanics of the encounter.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>eipen de to Pneuma tō Philippō</strong> (the Spirit said to Philip): the Spirit who directed Philip to leave Samaria now specifically directs him to approach the chariot. The mission is driven entirely by divine initiative — Philip did not select this target, assess the eunuch's readiness, or choose the moment. Luke uses 'Spirit said' (as opposed to 'angel said' in v.26) to mark the direct Spirit-prompting of the apostolic word.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>ara ge ginōskeis ha anaginōskeis</strong> (<em>ara ge ginōskeis ha anaginōskeis</em>, 'do you understand what you are reading?'): the <em>ara ge</em> formula is an inferential particle combination suggesting 'I take it then' — Philip's question is not impolite but engaged. The paronomasia (the same root <em>ginōskō/anaginōskō</em>) puns on knowing and reading: understanding requires more than literacy.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>pōs gar an dynaimen ean mē tis hodēgēsei me</strong> ('how can I, unless someone guides me?'): <em>hodēgēsē</em> (guide, lead the way) is the road-guide verb; the metaphor fits the chariot journey. The eunuch's honest acknowledgment of interpretive need is exactly the posture that opens him to Philip's instruction. He invites Philip up — the physical proximity enables the hermeneutical conversation.</p>",
    "32": "<p><strong>periochē tēs graphēs hēn anaginōsken</strong> ('the passage of Scripture he was reading'): <em>periochē</em> (section, passage) is a technical term for a scriptural unit. Isa 53:7-8 LXX is quoted verbatim; the LXX's <em>tēn genean autou tis diēgēsetai</em> diverges from the MT but makes the same point about the Servant's obscure destiny. The sheep-to-slaughter image and the silence of the shearee make Isa 53 the perfect locus for the eunuch's question.</p>",
    "33": "<p><strong>en tē tapeinōsei autou hē krisis autou ērthē</strong> ('in his humiliation his judgment was taken away'): the LXX reads differently from MT at this point; the Greek version the eunuch was reading has 'in his humiliation his judgment was removed' — his justice was denied, not that he was condemned. The verse supports the proclamation of the innocent sufferer. <strong>tis diēgēsetai tēn genean autou</strong>: 'who can tell of his descendants' — his life-line cut off, yet the community of believers is precisely that continuation.</p>",
    "34": "<p><strong>peri tinos ho prophētēs legei touto; peri heautou ē peri heterou tinos</strong> ('about whom does the prophet say this, about himself or about someone else?'): the eunuch's question is the decisive hermeneutical query — the same question the Qumran community asked of Isaiah. Philip's answer begins 'from this Scripture' (<em>apo tēs graphēs tautes</em>, v.35) and proceeds to Jesus: the prophet spoke of another, and that other is Jesus.</p>",
    "36": "<p><strong>idou hydōr; ti kōlyei me baptisthēnai</strong> ('look, water! what prevents me from being baptized?'): <em>kōlyō</em> (prevent, hinder) is Acts' baptism-readiness question; it reappears in 10:47 (Peter: 'can anyone withhold water?') and 11:17. The eunuch's spontaneous recognition that Philip's proclamation leads to baptism shows genuine understanding — he has connected the Isaiah Servant with Jesus with himself and with the covenant rite.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Verse 37 (Philip's 'if you believe with all your heart' exchange) is absent from the earliest and best manuscripts (P45, P74, Sinaiticus, Vaticanus) and is likely a scribal addition providing a baptismal confession formula for liturgical use. Its inclusion in later manuscripts reflects the growing importance of explicit pre-baptismal confession in church practice. The MKT notes its presence because some traditions rely on it.</p>",
    "38": "<p><strong>katebēsan amphoteroi eis to hydōr</strong> ('both went down into the water'): the immersion implied by <em>eis to hydōr</em> (into the water) and the parallel rising (<em>anebēsan ek tou hydatos</em>, v.39) supports baptism by immersion as the early form. The Sahidic Coptic and Ethiopian liturgical traditions made this the definitive text for immersion-practice; Philip's gesture of accompanying the eunuch into the water marks pastoral solidarity.</p>",
    "39": "<p><strong>pneuma kyriou hērpasen ton Philippon</strong> ('the Spirit of the Lord suddenly seized/snatched Philip'): <em>harpazō</em> (snatch, catch away) is the violent displacement verb — the same used for Paul's third heaven vision (2 Cor 12:2-4) and the Elijah/Elisha translation tradition (2 Kgs 2:16). Philip is providentially removed; the eunuch 'went on his way rejoicing' (<em>charōn</em>) — the joy-marker of arrival at salvation again.</p>",
    "40": "<p><strong>Azōton</strong> (Azotus/Ashdod): the Philistine city on the coastal plain; Philip's post-harpazō ministry moves northward through all the coastal towns until Caesarea, where he will appear again as the host of Paul (21:8). The coastal plain mission foreshadows the Gentile mission to come; Philip's itinerary traces a line that will become the spine of the Western Gentile expansion.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH9 = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p><strong>empneōn apeilēs kai phonou</strong> (<em>empneōn apeilēs kai phonou</em>, 'breathing out threats and murder'): <em>empneō</em> (breathe out) applied to threats makes Saul's hostility atmospheric — violence is his very breath. Luke's physicality intensifies the contrast with the new breath (<em>pnoē</em>) of the Spirit at Pentecost. Paul's retrospective self-description ('beyond measure I persecuted', Gal 1:13) matches Luke's characterization.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>hodos</strong> (<em>hē Hodos</em>, 'the Way'): Acts' preferred self-designation for the Christian movement (9:2; 19:9, 23; 22:4; 24:14, 22). The term may derive from Jesus's 'I am the Way' (John 14:6) or from Isa 40:3's 'way in the desert'; it presents the community as those traveling a specific path rather than holding a particular ideology — discipleship as direction of life. <strong>tēs synagōgēs grammata</strong>: letters to synagogues assert the high priest's judicial jurisdiction over diaspora Jews.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>exaiphnēs te auton periēstrapsen phōs ek tou ouranou</strong> ('suddenly a light from heaven flashed around him'): <em>exaiphnēs</em> (suddenly, immediately) marks the theophanic disruption; <em>periēstrapsen</em> (flashed around) describes the surrounding light of divine presence. The Damascus theophany will be narrated three times in Acts (9, 22, 26) — each retelling emphasizes different aspects for different audiences. Luke's frequency signals its foundational importance for the Gentile mission.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>Saoul Saoul ti me diōkeis</strong> ('Saul, Saul, why do you persecute me?'): the double-name vocative is the biblical marker of divine address at decisive moments (Abraham in Gen 22:11; Moses in Exod 3:4; Samuel in 1 Sam 3:10). The Hebrew form <em>Saoul</em> (not the Greek <em>Saulos</em>) suggests the voice addressed him in his own language — confirmed in 22:7 and 26:14 (Hebrew/Aramaic). The question 'why do you persecute me?' identifies the community's persecution with Christ's own.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>ego eimi Iēsous hon sy diōkeis</strong> ('I am Jesus whom you are persecuting'): the identification formula <em>ego eimi</em> (I am) echoes the divine self-disclosure of Exod 3:14 and the Johannine Christological formula. The risen Christ's identification of himself with his persecuted followers (not 'my followers' but 'me') is the foundation for the church's theology of suffering — to suffer for Christ is to suffer with Christ (Col 1:24; 2 Cor 1:5).</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>alla anastēthi kai eiselthe eis tēn polin</strong> ('but rise and enter the city'): <em>anastēthi</em> (rise) — the same imperative as resurrection proclamation — is the first word Saul hears from Jesus. He is directed to the city where he planned to arrest believers; the city becomes the place of his own transformation. The passive reception ('you will be told') keeps the initiative entirely divine.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>hestekeisan de enneoī hoi andres hoi synoiporountes</strong> ('the men traveling with him stood speechless'): <em>enneoi</em> (speechless, struck dumb) is a rare word for the stupor of shock. The companions present a corroboration problem: 22:9 says they saw the light but did not hear the voice; 9:7 says they heard the sound but saw no one. The different objects of 'hear' (<em>phōnē</em>) suggest they heard a sound without understanding the articulate speech Saul received.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>oiden oun Saulos apo tēs gēs ōnewgmenōn de tōn ophthalmōn autou ouden eblepēn</strong> ('Saul got up from the ground; when his eyes were opened he could see nothing'): the open eyes that see nothing are the paradox of the encounter — the persecutor who thought he saw clearly is now physically blind. Three days without sight or food mirrors the three days of the resurrection; Saul's transformation has a cruciform structure: the old Saul must die before the new Paul can rise.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>kai ēn hēmeras treis mē blepōn kai ouk ephagen oud' epien</strong> ('for three days he was blind and neither ate nor drank'): the three-day fast parallels Jonah's three days (Jonah 1:17) and the resurrection's three-day pattern. The blindness removes all of Saul's previous competencies — he who pursued with authority is now led by the hand; the man who destroyed others' communities must now be cared for. The fast signals the gravity of the transition.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>mathētēs de tis ēn en Damasko onomati Hananias</strong> ('there was a disciple in Damascus named Ananias'): Ananias is identified only as <em>mathētēs</em> (disciple) — not an apostle, not a prominent figure, but an ordinary member of the Damascus community. The Lord speaks to him in a vision (<em>en horamati</em>), using the same address-form as to Saul — the divine initiative reaches both persecutor and ordinary believer simultaneously.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>Saulos gar idou proseuchetai</strong> ('for behold, Saul is praying'): the word the Lord gives Ananias as reassurance is that Saul is praying — the one who came to arrest those who call on the name is himself now calling on the name. The <em>idou</em> (behold) marks this as surprising evidence: the persecutor in prayer is the visible sign of his transformation before any baptism or anointing.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>kai eiden andra onomati Hananias eiselthonta kai epithenta autō cheiras</strong> ('and he has seen a man named Ananias come and place hands on him'): the double-vision structure (Saul's vision of Ananias, Ananias's vision of the Lord) interlocks to confirm the divine coordination of the encounter. The Lord has prepared both parties simultaneously; neither is acting on their own discernment alone.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>kyrie, ēkousa apo pollōn peri tou andros toutou</strong> ('Lord, I have heard from many about this man'): Ananias's hesitation is presented without editorial criticism — it is reasonable protest based on real intelligence. The community's experience of Saul's persecution is the valid ground for Ananias's fear; the Lord's response does not rebuke the hesitation but overrides it with a larger purpose.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>tous epikaloumenous to onoma sou</strong> ('those who call on your name'): the community is defined by its practice of calling on the name — the Joel-quotation (2:21) made 'calling on the name of the Lord' the salvation criterion; the Damascus disciples are those who do this. Saul came to arrest those who call on the name; the Lord who is called upon is sending him back to serve the community he persecuted.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>skeuos eklogēs estin moi houtos</strong> ('this man is my chosen instrument'): <em>skeuos</em> (vessel, instrument) is used for functional objects; Paul becomes in Acts the vessel through which the mission extends to Gentiles, kings, and Israel. <em>Eklogē</em> (election, choice) grounds the appointment in divine prerogative — Paul will later describe his conversion as grace 'from my mother's womb' (Gal 1:15-16). The three-part scope (Gentiles, kings, Israel) matches Acts' narrative structure through ch.28.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>dei gar auton hypodeixai hosa dei auton hyper tou onomatos mou pathein</strong> ('for I will show him how much he must suffer for my name'): the repeated <em>dei</em> (it is necessary) frames Saul's future suffering as divinely ordained — the same necessity that governed Jesus's own passion (Luke 9:22; 22:37). The persecutor will become the persecuted; the man who made others suffer for the name will himself suffer for the name. Paul's theology of the cross is grounded in this commission.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>adelphe Saoul</strong> ('Brother Saul'): Ananias's address is the decisive social act of reconciliation — the member of the community that Saul came to arrest calls him brother before the healing or baptism. The brotherhood precedes the restoration of sight; the community's embrace is the first sign of the transformation the Lord announced. The address echoes Peter's <em>adelphoi</em> to the Pentecost crowd.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>hōsei lepides apo tōn ophthalmōn autou</strong> ('something like scales from his eyes'): <em>lepides</em> (scales, flakes) is a medical or descriptive term for the film or crust that covered sightless eyes; the imagery of scales falling away is vivid and physical. <strong>anablepsas</strong> (seeing again): the <em>ana-</em> prefix indicates the restoration of what was lost — not new sight but returned sight. Baptism follows immediately; the sequence (sight → baptism → food → strength) marks a complete restoration.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>egeneto meta tōn en Damaskō mathētōn hēmeras tinas</strong> ('he spent some days with the disciples in Damascus'): Saul's first post-conversion community is the community he came to destroy. The 'some days' in Damascus before his synagogue preaching (v.20) and his later Arabian withdrawal (Gal 1:17) are reconciled if the Galatians period comes between the Damascus days and the Jerusalem visit.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>eutheōs en tais synagōgais ekērysso ton Iēsoun</strong> ('immediately in the synagogues he was proclaiming Jesus'): <em>eutheōs</em> (immediately) is Luke's signal for Spirit-driven urgency; no apprenticeship intervenes. The content is specified as proclaiming Jesus — the same object as Philip's Samaritan mission (v.5) — but now from one who knew the OT scripturally as well as Ananias's community did experientially.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>pantes de hoi akouontes existanto kai elegon</strong> ('all who heard were astonished and said'): the astonishment (<em>existanto</em>) is the same word used for Simon Magus's effect on the Samaritans (8:9, 11); the transformation of the destroyer into a proclaimer produces the same shock as a miracle. <strong>symbibazōn</strong> (demonstrating, proving): the verb means to bring together evidence to form a conclusion — Saul's method is demonstrative proof, not just assertion.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>pleiō de mallon enedunamōto</strong> ('he grew more and more powerful'): <em>enedunamoō</em> (strengthen, empower) is the Pauline growth verb (Phil 4:13; 2 Tim 4:17); the same power that Saul was trying to suppress in the church now characterizes his own ministry. <strong>symbibazōn hoti houtos estin ho Christos</strong> ('proving that this is the Messiah'): the same <em>symbibazōn</em> as v.22 — Saul is an exegetical demonstrator, reasoning from texts.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>hōs de eplērounto hēmerai hikanai</strong> ('when many days had passed'): the time-gap accommodates Paul's Galatians account of the Arabian withdrawal (Gal 1:17); Luke compresses a period that Paul describes as significant. <strong>synebouleusanto oi Ioudaioi anelein auton</strong> ('the Jews plotted to kill him'): the pattern will repeat throughout Acts — the same communities that opposed the apostles before Paul now oppose Paul. The persecutor suffers the persecution he inflicted.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>pareterounton de kai tas pylas hēmeras te kai nyktos hopōs auton anelōsin</strong> (they were watching the city gates day and night to kill him): the continuous <em>pareterounton</em> (keeping watch) shows the siege-mentality of the plot. Paul's account in 2 Cor 11:32 adds that the ethnarch of Aretas was also involved — a confluence of Jewish and Nabatean opposition. The basket escape (v.25) is one of Paul's most remembered humiliations (2 Cor 11:33).</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>labontes de hoi mathētai autou nyktos dia tou teichous kathēkan auton chalasantes en spyridi</strong> ('his disciples lowered him through the wall at night in a basket'): <em>spyris</em> is a large wicker or rope basket; the escape method is both practical and ironic — the zealot who came bearing arrest-letters is smuggled out like cargo. The community (now <em>hoi mathētai autou</em>, 'his disciples') that he came to destroy now protects him.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>peirāto kollasthai tois mathētais; kai pantes ephobounto auton</strong> ('he tried to join the disciples, but all were afraid of him'): <em>kollaomai</em> (attach oneself to, associate with) is the social-bonding verb; the Jerusalem community's fear is entirely understandable. The irony continues: Saul whose letters authorized the arrest of believers is now himself treated as a security threat by the community he wants to join.</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>Barnabas de epilabomenos auton ēgagen pros tous apostolous</strong> ('but Barnabas took hold of him and brought him to the apostles'): <em>epilambanomai</em> (take hold of, grasp) implies an initiative Barnabas took without being asked. Barnabas (named 'son of encouragement' in 4:36) becomes the advocate whose personal vouching enables Saul's reception. The report he gives — Damascus road event, Damascus preaching boldly — establishes the apostolic authentication Saul needed.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>eisporeuomenos kai ekporeuomenos eis Ierousalēm parrēsiazomenos en tō onomati tou kyriou</strong> ('moving freely in Jerusalem, speaking boldly in the name of the Lord'): <em>eisporeuomenos kai ekporeuomenos</em> (going in and out) is the Septuagintal idiom for active public ministry (the same phrase Ananias used to describe Jesus's ministry in 1:21). <em>Parrēsiazomenos</em> (speaking boldly) is Acts' marker of Spirit-empowered public testimony.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>elalei te kai sunezētei pros tous Hellēnistas</strong> ('he was speaking and debating with the Hellenistic Jews'): Saul's natural constituency — Greek-speaking diaspora Jews in Jerusalem — is the same community that martyred Stephen (6:9). The debate partners who killed Stephen now try to kill Saul; his conversion has transferred him from persecutor to persecuted within the same Hellenistic Jewish milieu.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>katēgagon auton eis Kaisareian kai exapesteilan auton eis Tarson</strong> ('they brought him down to Caesarea and sent him off to Tarsus'): Tarsus is Saul's home city (22:3), a safe haven that also positions him in the region of Cilicia and Syria where Gal 1:21 places his early ministry. The Caesarea → Tarsus route (by sea) removes him from the Jerusalem danger; God has arranged Saul's brief Jerusalem visit (15 days, Gal 1:18) and now provides the escape route.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>hē men oun ekklēsia kath' holēs tēs Ioudaias kai Galilaiias kai Samareias eichen eirēnēn oikodoumoumenē</strong> ('the church throughout Judea, Galilee, and Samaria had peace and was built up'): Luke's summary statement covers the three regions of Acts 1:8's mandate. <em>Oikodomeō</em> (build up) is the Pauline church-building metaphor (1 Cor 3:9-15; Eph 2:20-22); the church's growth in peacetime has the same architectural structure. <strong>tō phobō tou kyriou ... tē paraklēsei tou hagiou pneumatos</strong>: the twin modes of community formation — reverential fear and Spirit-encouragement.</p>",
    "32": "<p><strong>egeneto de Petron dierchoumenon dia pantōn katelthein kai pros tous hagious tous katoikountas Lydda</strong> ('Peter went to visit the saints who lived in Lydda'): <em>tous hagious</em> (the saints/holy ones) is the covenant-community designation derived from OT <em>qedoshim</em>; it is Paul's standard address in his letters and appears here in Luke for what seems the first time in Acts. The Lydda-Joppa-Caesarea narrative (9:32-10:48) traces Peter's coastal journey toward the pivotal Cornelius encounter.</p>",
    "33": "<p><strong>Iēsous Christos iatai se</strong> ('Jesus Christ heals you'): Peter does not invoke the name as a formula but makes a direct declarative statement — the healing is Jesus Christ's action, with Peter as the instrument. <em>Strōson seautō</em> ('make your bed/mat'): the practical instruction confirms the healing's completeness — not merely restored sensation but immediate functional capacity.</p>",
    "34": "<p><strong>pantes hoi katoikountes Lydda kai ton Sarōna hoi tines epestrepsan epi ton kyrion</strong> ('all who lived in Lydda and Sharon turned to the Lord'): the geographic specificity (Lydda and the Sharon plain) grounds the mission in identifiable territory; these villages would later become significant in the Jewish-Christian communities of the second century. The mass turning (<em>epestrepsan</em>) precedes the Cornelius episode — the coastal plain is being prepared for the Gentile breakthrough.</p>",
    "35": "<p><strong>mathētria tis ēn en Ioppē onomati Tabitha</strong> ('there was a disciple named Tabitha'): <em>mathētria</em> (female disciple) is a hapax in the NT — the only occurrence of the feminine form. Luke's use of it for Tabitha is deliberate: she is not merely a helper or patron but a disciple in her own right. The bilingual name (<em>Dorkas</em> in Greek = gazelle) shows her integration into both Jewish and Hellenistic communities. Her <em>ergōn agathōn kai eleēmosynōn</em> (good works and almsgiving) are the marks of active covenant-community life.</p>",
    "36": "<p><strong>egeneto de en tais hēmerais ekeinais asthenēsasan autēn apothanein</strong> ('in those days she became ill and died'): the temporal marker <em>en tais hēmerais ekeinais</em> connects Tabitha's death to the Lydda mission, setting up Peter's proximity as providential. The preparation of her body (<em>lousantes ethekan en hyperōō</em>, washed and placed in the upper room) is Jewish burial preparation; the upper room is the same distinctive Jerusalem Christian meeting space (1:13; 20:8).</p>",
    "37": "<p><strong>aposteilantes duo andras pros auton parekaloun</strong> ('sending two men they urged him'): the two-man delegation mirrors the pattern of official mission (10:7; Luke 10:1); the urgency of their request — Peter is nearby, the death is recent — suggests they expected or hoped for resurrection, not merely comfort. The appeal to 'not delay in coming' (<em>mē okneō dielthein heōs hēmōn</em>) is the language of life-or-death urgency.</p>",
    "38": "<p><strong>pasai hai chērai pareistēkeisan autō klaious ai kai epideiknymena chitōnas kai himatia</strong> ('all the widows stood around him weeping and showing tunics and cloaks'): the widows' display of Tabitha's work is both a testimony to her ministry and an appeal grounded in relationship. The clothing she made for them represents her <em>eleēmosyne</em> (almsgiving) made concrete; the community's grief is proportional to the loss of a specific, irreplaceable benefactor.</p>",
    "39": "<p><strong>ekteinasa de Petros ta gonata proseuxato</strong> ('Peter knelt down and prayed'): Peter's kneeling prayer before the miracle reproduces the pattern of Jesus's prayer before raising Lazarus (John 11:41-42). The dependence on the Father is explicit: Peter does not command the resurrection but prepares through prayer. The contrast with Jesus's immediate word of command (Luke 8:54) is intentional — the apostle acts in Christ's name and power, not in his own authority.</p>",
    "40": "<p><strong>Tabitha, anastēthi</strong> ('Tabitha, arise'): the Aramaic retention matches Jesus's <em>Talitha koum</em> at Jairus's daughter (Mark 5:41); the parallel is deliberate — Peter raising Tabitha is the apostolic continuation of Jesus's resurrection-ministry. <strong>aneblepsas kai idousa ton Petron anekathisen</strong> ('opening her eyes and seeing Peter, she sat up'): the sequence — eyes open, recognizes Peter, sits up — mirrors awakening from sleep, which is Acts' consistent resurrection imagery.</p>",
    "41": "<p><strong>dous de autē cheira anestēsen autēn</strong> ('taking her by the hand he helped her up'): the raising-by-the-hand echoes Jesus's gesture with Jairus's daughter (Mark 5:41; Luke 8:54) and Peter's raising of the lame man (3:7). The bodily, physical touch is the sign of genuine resurrection — not a vision or spiritual experience but a hand grasped and a person lifted. <em>Tois hagiois kai tais chērais</em>: Peter presents her to both the whole community and the widows specifically — the most affected are the first to receive her back.</p>",
    "42": "<p><strong>gnōston de egeneto kath' holēs tēs Ioppēs kai episteusan polloi epi ton kyrion</strong> ('this became known throughout Joppa and many believed in the Lord'): the Tabitha resurrection is the anchor event for the Joppa community; the same pattern of miracle → belief → community-expansion governs the Lydda and Sharon response (v.35). Joppa is the city where Jonah boarded the ship to flee; it becomes the city where Peter receives the vision that sends him to the Gentiles (ch.10).</p>",
    "43": "<p><strong>egeneto de hēmeras hikanas meinai en Ioppē para tini Simōni bursει</strong> ('he stayed in Joppa for some time with a tanner named Simon'): a tanner's work with animal hides made him ritually impure by Jewish standards; Peter's willingness to lodge with him is a first step toward the boundary-crossing that the Cornelius episode will complete. Luke's geographic and social placement of Peter here prepares the reader for the vision of unclean animals that will challenge Peter's purity-map in ch.10.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-original', 'acts')
    merge_comm(existing, ORIGINAL)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH8)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH9)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'acts', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Acts mkt-original: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
